{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_flicker_ver02/data/sn87093042/00332890025/1937111801/0071.xml":{"full_text":"6\ni: _r, -\u2014--'=r\" =7l\n(\u201cx 3 9 AF: W. \"I!\n_ j- \ufb02 E\nEgg-\"Lg \"a\u2018m\u2019\u00e9y\u00e9i\n:J U\u201d dim\u201c\nNatxonal Togics Interpreted [ls m\nby William Bruckart WK\nNatinnal Press Buihlim: W Washington. D. C. 1f...\"\nNew Experiment\nWashington\u2014Supporters of the\nNew Deal as well as its opponents\nare watching a new experiment by\nPresident Roosevelt with more than\npassing interest. They are watch\ning this experiment because of var\nious circumstanaces including ob\nviously its political phases for they\nrealize that the President has step\nped out into a hitherto untrod field,\nunplowed ground in this new exper\niment.\nChiefly because it is something\nentirely new and not because any\none yet can tell what is going to\nhappen I want to report this week\non the President's plan to have his\neldest son James, his No. 1 sec\nretary, serve as a clearing house\nbetween the Chief Executive and\nsome eighteen or more government\nagencies. Roosevelt, the younger,\nhas been designated by the Presi\ndent to sit down once each week\nwith the heads of the enumerated\nagencies and talk over their prob\nlems, iron out those which he can\nhelp solve, co-ordinate the work be\ntween them as far as he is able to\ndo so and, most important to the\nmen with whom he deals. decide\nwhich questions confronting these\nunits of government may be mat\nters for the President\u2019s personal\nconsideration.\nIt is a big order. But Jimmy as\nhe is known around here is a big\nman at least physically because he\nstands something like six feet one\ninch. He is twenty-nine years old.\nThe audiences at the White House\nwith Jimmy have already started\nand the agency heads who have sat\nthrough the conferences seem well\npleased. At least. there has been\nno criticism yet. no signs of jealousy\nor indications of diment among\nthose who are called upon to take\nup their problems with the young\nsecretary to the Preseident. In fact,\nIhaveheardinonlyafewplacesa\nrevival of the punning that went\nout a couple of years ago when the\n\u201cRoosevelt for King\" game was in\nits heyday, and Jimmy was laugh\ningiy labeled as the crown prince.\n'l'huatheplansurelyseemstohave\nstarted off most suspiciously. But\nas I said what success what trials\nand tribulations, await it. no one\ncan say.\nMuch in [ln Favor\nUndoubtedly President Roosevelt\nhasstartedaplanofactionthathaa\nImuch to be said in its favor. It has\n\u20180! course many possibilities of trou\niile and there surely is argument\n\ufb01shinst having the White House\n\"-\u2018Be\ufb02etariat determine policy when\nthe President has been elected to\nthat job. Yet at this time credit\nimust be argued along with signs\nand portents of trouble.\n[Firstletmreeognizethattheof\ntice of President of the United\n*States is a man-killing job. There\nis nothing like it anywhere else in\nithe world There are not too many\n'men who can stand up under the\nload of work and worry that is con\n:tinually on the shoulders or the\n-head of the nation. There is no\n:yay possible for him to escape it.\n_Vacations? Sleep? Absence from\nWashington? Not a chance. The\n\u2018work and worry is with him always\n\u201cevery minute out of his twenty-four\nhaour day.\nThus it there is any way that\ncan be devised to lift some of the\nburden it ought to be done. No\nway has been found heretofore,\nhow-ever, and the millstone contin-\\\nues around the President's neck. 1\nOn the other hand this is a de\u00bb\nmocracy. In the opinion of many\npersons there already is too much\npower lodged in the hands or in\ndividuals who were not elected but\nwere appointed to office. The Pres\nident has vast power and he has to\nunload it somewhere into the hands\nor those he appoints. Nevertheless\nthroughout the federal government\nscores of men and women exercise\nvery great authority over your life\nand mine who were personally se\nlected by the President-401' whom\nnone or us voted when we voted for\na presidential nominee. Result: red\ntape rules and regulations. do\u2019s and\ndon\u2019ts galore until we hardly know\nwhether we can eat our food with\nout transgressing or failing to com-\n391! with some federal regulations\nAll of that is by way of saying\u2018\n\u2018that by implementing the relaw\ntionship between the President andi\nmen and Women whom he has ap-j\npointed to office through the inser\ntion of an added wheel of author\nity, there lie potential changes in all\nof these governmental policies And\nthere lies the possibility of changes\nbeing made, for better or for worse,\nwithout the Preddent having any\nknowledge of then.\nWhat of the personal side the\nfeelings of the officials who have\nto deal with a young man who can\nspeak, to some artent at least. for\nhis father, the President. As I said\nearlier, thus far none of the con\nferees have given any indication of\ndisturbed feelings. They may never\nhave any thoughts along this line.\nYet, I venture this observation: if\nthey don\u2019t resent having the Presi\ndent\u2019s son tell them what to do or\nnot to do at some time or other. the\nofficials concerned will be unlike\nmost other human beings.\nBusiness Outlook\nThe Department of Agriculture is\nquite pessimistic about the business\noutlook for next year. In a series\nof reports. analyzing general condi\ntions, which the department issued\nthe other day, it made no effort to\nconceal its belief that there is some\nthing wrong in the business situa\ntion far beyond the recent violent\ndecline in the quotations of the\nstock markets.\nThese reports and conclusions\n7 take on considerably more weight\nwhen it is recalled that several\nother agencies of the government,\nnotably Secretary Roper of the De\npartment of Commerce. have sought\nvainly to make it appear that bus\niness is \u201cgood.\u201d At the same time\nI think attention ought to be drawn\nto the fact that Secretary Wallace\nof the Department of Agriculture is\nstriving to have congress pass legisi\nlation to aid the farmer. It is just\npossible that he thinks his object\nives can be achieved more easily if\nthe congressmen are made to believe\nthat general business and agricul\nture are taking a real tailspin. That\nis the politics of the situation but.\nbusiness reports spread on the pages\nof newspapers seem to show that a\nbad slump lies ahead.\nRecently. I wrote in these col\numns how business was as spotted as\na leopard; that some firms were\nmaking more money than ever be\nfore and how some others were get\nting by only because the volume\nwas large and faced difficulties if\nthe volume declined. The Agricul\nture Department statements, based\nnow on facts and figures, show even\na worse pictm'e than I described\nseveral months ago. They indicate\nstrongly that 1938 is to be consider\nably lower in the level of business\nthan 1937 and that spells trouble.\nFor example the agriculture state\nment predictsthat there will be a\n\u201cless favorable demand for farm\n[products\u2019 in 1933 than in 1937. The\nIhome domestic demands are down\nand appear likely to stay down.\nand the export market holds no\nhope for an increase. Emphasizing\nthe dependence of consumption de\nmand upon general business condi\ntions. the department statement ex\nplained there was no certainty as to\nthe length of time the present slump\nwill continue. It added that \u201cprosp\npects are against a sufficiently ear\nly and vigorous rise in 1938 to bring\nthe average of industrial activity\nand of consumer incomes up to that\nof 1937\u201d\nPicture Made Worse\nBut _from the standpoint of the\nfarmer, the picture is made worse\nby the department statement It\npointsouthowtherehasbeenarise\nin production costs of crops and\nlivestock and how. staring the farm-\nTHE FEATHERHEADS \"2%\"...\nMESCAL IKE n, s. I. 11mm.\"\n\u201cAFB\n'.\u2019MATI\u2018ER POP\u2014 Pop Came Back Down Later\ner in the face, are more of these in\ncreasos, adding:\n\u201cAlong with the higher wage\nrates, farmers apparently will have\nto pay somewhat higher prices for\nfarm machinery, automobiles, build\ning materials, equipment and sup\nplies. On the other hand the prices\nof feed and seed Will be substan\ntially lower next spring than a year\nearlier\u201d\nThe department did not go into\ndetail in explaining these increases\nin production costs and increases in\nlprices for things the farmer buys.\nIt should have given facts and fig\nures on these for they are basic and\nthe picture is incomplete without\nthem. Everyone knows of course\nthat farm labor wants more money\nfor its work and has been getting\n,more in the last two or three years.\nDepartment of Labor statistics show\nthis and they show as well how\nmuch additional labor is receiving\nin its pay checks from industry. The\nautomobile industry which has been\nlorganized by John L. Lewis and\nI his C. 1.0. labor group has been forc\n\u2019ed to pay much higher wages and\nI naturally those wages have been\nadded into the cost of the automo\nbile which any one buys.\nThe automobile industry was only\nan illustration. The same is true\nall along the line.\nThe truth of the matter is that\nli\u2019ederal taxes which have geen con\nceived by the President\u2019s brain trust\nprofessors and applied without stint;\nor limit to industry are upsetting\u2018\nthe whole agricultural as well as thel\nwhole business structure of thel\ncountry. The load of taxes togeth\ner with a lot of queer-looking and\ncock-eyed regulations have continu\nally increased the cost of production\nof every thing from black-eyed peas\nto locomotives. It follows always\nthat the balance between supply and\ndemand is upset notwithstanding\nthe conviction that some men have\nof their ability to amend the law of\nsupply and demand.\nTwo Commanders Killed\nCapt. Samuel Blythe commanded\nthe brig Boxer. which was engaged\nin 1813 by the American brig En\nterprise, commanded by William\nBurrows. At the \ufb01rst exchange of\nbroadsides. both commanders tell:\nBlythe was killed instantly. Burrows\nwas mortally wounded. The Boxer\nwas raked until it surrendered. then\ntaken into Portland as a prize.\nFirst Balloon Flight\nOn October 15. 1783. the \ufb01rst ac\ntual ascent was made when Pilatre\nde Rozier made several captive as\ncents in a Mongol\ufb01er balloon in\nParis. On November 21. 1783. the\n\ufb01rst tree ascent was made by de\nRozier and the Marquis d\u2019Arlandes.\nwho. ascending from the Chateau\nde la Muette. made a voyage last\ning about 20 minutes.\nMeaning of Chuuvinlsm\nThe word Chauvinism. which\nmeans unreasonable and exaggerat~\ned patriotism. formerly signi\ufb01ed\nidolatry of Napoleon. being taken\ntram the name of a much-wounded\nveteran. Nicholas Chauvin, who by\nhis blind adoration of the emperor\nbecame the type of worship 0! mil\nitary glory.\nWPA Correspondence\nOffers Opportunities\nAn opportunity for correspondence\nstudy in a wide range of subjects is\noffered by the Division of Educa\ntion, Works Progress Administration,\nto those who wish to broaden their\neducation or improve their leisure\ntime.\nThese courses have been super\nvised by professors of the University\nof Washington. and are on the Col\nlege Level. Courses are offered in\nagriculture, business administration\nand economics. education, history,\nhome economics, horticulture. poli\ntical science. sociology. and religion,\na total of more than 125 courses\nCollege credit is granted upon sat\nisfactory completion of the courses\nselected and matriculation in one\nof the several colleges of the state.\nTpere is no fee and the only costs\nare hose of text books and postage.\nWHSTRANGE BUT TRUE\ufb02\nWINTER IS COMING\nGet in your coal supply now, and take advan-\ntage of present savings! Standard gives you\nmore value per dollar every time! Goals in all 1\ngrades are chosen for their heat value, low ash\ncontent, and dustless qualities. Standard has\na coal for every need!\nSTANDARD LUMBER CO.\n1 w. 'J. SKINNER, Manager I\nThe student pmceeds as rapidly us\nhedesires.\nMrs. P ranoes Kingston. 1:. A.. has\nbeenplaoedinchargeoftheworkin\nthe Yakima vicinity. For further\ninformation in regard to these\ncourses, see her at the Yakima Sen\nior high school Monday. Wednesday\nand Friday nights. from 7 to 10. or\nwrite her at 923 East Chestnut St..\nYakima.\nUnited States Flag on Wake [shad\nThe United States \ufb02ag on Wake\nIsland was hoisted on July 4. 1898.\nIt is on the direct route between\nHawaii and Hongkong. about 2.000\nmiles from Hawaii and 3.000 miles\nfrom Hongkong.\nHighest Lower Michigan Peak\nThe highest point in the Lower\npeninsula of Michigan is seven\nmiles south and three miles east of\nCadillac. The elevation is 1.712 feet\nabove sea level.\nV\u2014\u2014\u2019\n(Gown-um. U! I. I. \"an\". M. mM.U. C. P\u201c. Ollo\u201d I\nThe .Art of Brewing 34\nNo. 5. FILTERING for Drauglu 3Q\nand Bottling Departments\n\u00abscanning mm: Beverage of Millions \u00abINN;\nA o the cellar where the government measure: I\nnew I the amount of beer going into bottles. and M\nm'rmmc The beer is now fil\ntened {or brillinncy. It then is needy to\nbe mnefened as needed to the draught\nwe: and bottled beer depmenu. For\nthe draught depnmnent. it goes directly\nno the keg \ufb01lling mchine. end for hot\ntling. it pee though the government\nbonded pipe line end metering tanks to\nthe holding depmt. end from theme\nEvery process of Olympic brewing is improved by the\nexceptional' ham qualma' and constant purity\nour [m subterranean m \u201cIf: the My};\nonmn 33mm comm, OLYMPIA. VAsmNcmg. a.\u201c\nPICKED UP\nAROUND TOWN\nRaubenGestuysmatsinoethe\nelecu'lcchnirdoesn\u2019toeemtohave\nndneedalmeltmlchtbeagood\nmmmmmmm.\nJ J J\n\u201cYou can\u2018t all s girl's complexion\n\u2018aMht\ufb02ushmys\u201ddecm\nEvelyn Mann \u201cbecause quite\nmmqgetltonaooked.\u201d\n'JJ J 1\nThedlverlnh